Subject: 3. What is appropriate to post, what isn't?

  In the next few paragraphs, we'll try to shed light on a
    number of questions.  The Usenet Marketplace is NOT 
    equivalent to your local newspaper's classifieds, so
    we ask that you follow the proper guidelines when
    advertising.  If, after reading this section, you still
    don't know if you should post or not, send e-mail to

  	  dank@metrics.com

    He'll be glad to help you out.

  Oh, by the way, have you read the articles on netiquette in
    news.announce.newusers yet?  Please do so before posting.

  IF YOU ARE AN INDIVIDUAL just trying to get rid of something
    you don't want anymore, then it's easy.  You may post to the
    appropriate misc.forsale.* group.  Read the rest of this
    FAQ before posting, as it will help you get the best
    response to your ad.  Auctions are permitted, but frowned 
    upon by some users.  Please limit duration to 2 weeks and
    2 updates or reminders.

  Question:  "So-and-so posted an item with a high price.  May I
	warn everyone else?"
  Answer:  No.  The readers of misc.forsale and biz.marketplace
	are adults who know when a price is inflated.  Instead,
	send e-mail directly to the poster.  Usually, he/she
	will be more than happy to correct the article if you
	politely inform him/her where a better price can be
	Especially with computer items, the market is
	established and prices are relatively well-known to
	anyone considering a purchase--even if a seller or two
	are clueless.

  Question:  "I want to post ... as a joke."
	(i.e. offer a 286SX for $4000)
  Question:  "I want to forward this chain letter.  It's legal,
	you know..."
  Question:  "I want to post a test article..."
  Answer: NO, NO, NO, NO, NO, and NO.  If you waste the bandwidth,
	expect complaints in your mailbox and your system
	administrator's mailbox.  Chain letters of *any* 
	kind are absolutely verboten at most Usenet sites.  Jokes
	waste the time of many readers who read news at work.  
	Tests also waste time.  They have their own groups, like
	misc.test.  Abuse of the Usenet in this manner has
	caused scores of people to lose their account privileges
	at many different sites.  We depend on all of our users to
	help maintain the usefulness of the newsgroups.  If you
	find someone posting inappropriately, please let him/her
	know with a polite message.  More than likely, they don't
	even know this FAQ exists--help us to steer them towards
	it.

  IF YOU ARE AN ENTREPRENEUR OR BUSINESS, then posting
    can be tricky.  Your arena is biz.marketplace.*.

	Rule #1:  You may advertise your wares if they provide an
	  advantage not available from other easily-accessible
	  vendors.  That means you have a better price or a better
	  product that can't be found through retail stores,
	  mail-order catalogs, or national magazines like Computer
	  Shopper.

	When you advertise, you must state exact items/services
	  for sale.  Just brand names or types of products are
	  unacceptable.  Anyone who reads your article must be
	  able to figure out that you do have the best price
	  or product.  Your ad must include pertinent technical
	  and shipping details as well.
	
	If your entire catalog has excellent pricing, you may
	  NOT post the entire catalog.  Instead, pick a few
	  choice items with the biggest price differential and
	  of widespread popularity, and post their prices.  As
	  long as you provide a few examples, it is o.k. to
	  solicit e-mail requests for your catalog.  DO NOT
	  just post an article saying 'reply for more information'.
	  YOU MUST include examples which demonstrate the
	  appropriateness of your ad.

	In any case, commercial/entrepreneurial ads should be
	  no more than 1-2 screenfuls (~35 lines) in length.

	Rule #2:  As with any other post, you must make several
	  posts if you are selling items which belong in
 	  different groups.  DO NOT POST ONE ARTICLE TO MANY
	  GROUPS.  This wastes readers' time, as readers are
	  usually looking for a specific item.  They hate
	  wasting their time, and will usually ignore your
	  article--even if it has what they're looking for...

	Rule #3:  Marketing hype is NOT ALLOWED.
	
	MOST IMPORTANT RULE #4:  If your advantage is pricing,
	  then every item you are offering must have a price
	  quote in the article.  That quote MUST be
	  *significantly* lower than ANY nationally-obtainable
	  price for the same item new.  That means retail AND
	  mail-order prices.  For computer items, the guide is
	  the lowest price in Computer Shopper.  If your item
	  is 'not sold in stores,' so to speak, that's fine.
	  Make sure you include a competitive price for the
	  value offered.  After all, that's what buyers expect
	  on the Usenet Marketplace--the best prices available.

  Question:  "In MOST IMPORTANT RULE #4:, what does *significantly*
	lower mean?"
  Answer:  Here's the general guide--
		Price of item	  Savings over best national price
		  $0 < x < $200		at least $20
		  $200 < x < $500	at least $30
		     x > $500		at least $40-50
	   Or, roughly, savings on more expensive items must be 10%.
	   Obviously, the rules change when dealing in quantity,
	      but the 10% minimum is a fair estimate.

  Question:  "What about if my ad is about a service, rather than
	a specific item?"
  Answer:  You may post to the appropriate biz.marketplace.services
	group, subject to all pertinent conditions above.  That
	means:
		It must be of interest to many readers,
		It must be less expensive than available nationally,
		Specific details must be given in the article, and
		NO HYPE.

