Subject: 5. How do you write an effective ad for Usenet?

  The best way to learn is to watch others.  Read a number of
    ads, then tailor yours to fit your needs.  On the
    Usenet Marketplace, hype is considered bad form.  All we
    need are the facts--the more the better.

  First, divide up your items into appropriate groupings.  Make
    separate ads for items which belong in different groups, so
    you can avoid crossposting.  Then come up with a Subject:
    line for each post.  Limit yourself to about 35 characters
    (including spaces), but be as descriptive as possible.  A
    subject line of:
	'Monitor for sale'
    will be much less noticed in m.fs.computers.monitors than:
	'14" Samtron SVGA Monitor for sale.'
    Along the same lines:
	'Household items for sale'
    is just asking to be skipped.  Instead, try:
	'Iron, Speakers, Cherry Pitter For Sale'
    as you'll get a much better response. The words 'For Sale'
    are recommended in the subject if you have the room, but 
    it's better to include more information instead.

  If you are writing a WANTED ad, again, be as specific as
    possible, but BE SURE to include WANTED: in the title.
    Readers get very frustrated with people who never say
    'Wanted' until the last line of their ad.

  Now that you have a descriptive title, you need to build the
    body.  All good ads on the Usenet Marketplace fit on one
    screen and include the following:
	Item, Manufacturer, Model, and Age
	Important technical details
	Aftermarket Add-Ons/Upgrades

    And, some additional necessary information:
	Your full name and e-mail address
	Any warranty you will provide, or lack thereof
		(Working on Arrival is standard practice)
	Your location (e.g., city & state), and your willingness
		to ship the item elsewhere
	Who pays for shipping?
	Why are you selling the item?
		(businesses, is it refurbished/overstock/...?)

    And, most important of all:
	YOUR ASKING PRICE, or, alternatively, solicit offers.
	Is your price firm, or will you accept offers?
	
    Before you forget to include a price, remember the old adage,
	"If you gotta ask, you don't want to know."
    Such is the mentality on Usenet.

  This tried-and-true format is the most successful way to
    advertise on the Usenet Marketplace.  Hype helps no one
    and wastes resources.  Factual information works better.
    Again, readers on the Usenet Marketplace know what they
    are looking for.  If you post junk, you won't get any
    response.

  Finally, ONCE YOUR ITEM HAS SOLD, PLEASE CANCEL YOUR ARTICLE.
    This simple, easy gesture will save the time of thousands
    of people who won't have to read your article any more.  It
    will also save you from having to respond to messages from
    people who don't know your item has sold.  In many
    newsreaders, you can cancel an article by pressing a capital
    "C" while reading the article.  However, this varies from
    site to site.  Please find out how to cancel an article from
    someone locally BEFORE you post your ad.	

