Subject: 6. Considerations for commercial/entrepreneurial ads.

  At last count, some 300,000 people read at least one of the Usenet
    Marketplace groups.  What better audience for many commercial
    advertisers, particularly those offering computer wares!
    Unfortunately, over the last couple of years, many undereducated
    commercial advertisers have given commercial entities, in general,
    a bad connotation on Usenet.  Because of this, businesses and
    entrepreneurs need to pay especially close attention to the rules
    and recommendations of posting.  I guarantee that response to
    your ads will be significantly more positive if you follow the
    recommendations presented thus far.  The rest of this section is
    devoted to clarifying a few of the points, and to explain some of
    the reasons why you should take the extra time to prepare your
    marketing strategy.

  Question:  "Why can't for-profit entities post in the misc.forsale
	groups?"
  Answer:
	This is likely the most frequently asked question in the
    misc.forsale groups.  It can be particularly confusing, since
    so many other people do post commercial ads in misc.forsale.*
    [erroneously], and because most software allows them to post.
	Two main points are brought up every time this question is
    asked.  First, the backbone of Usenet is maintained primarily by
    government agencies and educational institutions.  Most news
    articles you read are transmitted over the Internet, which serves
    as the major backbone of Usenet.  The Internet was originally
    developed to provide a means for the dissemination of research
    and government information.  Companies began to hook onto the
    Internet in order to exchange research information with
    educational institutions.  The problem is that many of the
    non-commercial entities who host the backbone do not endorse
    commercial entities, nor do they approve of commercial use of
    their resources.  Especially with universities--often the
    'local distributors' of the Internet from regional government
    'hubs', commercial use is often forbidden because they don't
    have the resources to spare on 'free' advertising.  While it may
    only cost you pennies to post, netwide commercial advertising
    requires an additional 20-30 megabytes of hard disk space at
    each of thousands of sites worldwide.  Biz.*, on the other hand,
    is a hierachy intended for commercial entities.  As a result,
    many educational institutions don't carry it--although that is
    changing.  As more and more benefits to carrying biz.* accrue--
    like the computer-purchasing advantages of b.m.computers.*,
    these sites choose to subscribe to biz.*.  The important point
    is *choose*.  With misc.*, they don't have a choice in the
    matter, so they complain.  When they choose to carry biz.*,
    they lose their argument.

  As a commercial/entrepreneurial poster, you carry a lot of
    weight on your shoulders.  Because of poor judgment on the
    part of your predecessors, you need to be particularly
    careful to follow the guidelines above in order for the
    Usenet to be willing to allow you to post at all.  In
    addition to the above, I STRONGLY suggest you be prepared
    for a few additional points before posting:

    #1:  If your services or items are available on a continuous
	basis, keep a 30-day interval between your posts (unless
	there is a change which needs mentioning sooner--see #3).
	More frequent posts waste bandwidth and turn the Usenet
	against	you.

    #2:  If you are using an automated response system to 
	anyone who sends e-mail in response to your ad, be sure
	you include an e-mail address at the bottom of your ad
	to which potential customers can send questions or
	comments to a human being.  Automated servers are good
	for many things	on the Internet, but they do not always 
	work for responding to ad inquiries.  You may lose
	business, or other users may complain to your system
	administrator if they can't reach you.  

    #3:  Make certain that you have the capability of, and know
	how to cancel your article if necessary.  If you make a
	mistake when posting, or you need to revise your ad,
	it is imperative that you be able to cancel it quickly.
	Otherwise, you may be inundated with hate mail or worse.
	The most universal way to correct such problems is to
	post a corrected ad with a Supersedes: header at the top
	of your message.  To do	this, you need the Message-ID:
	from your original article.  Go into your newsreader,
	find your article, and look at the headers (you may need
	to hit 'h' to see them).  Among them should be:

	Newsgroups: misc.forsale.non-computer
	Subject: BooBoo For Sale
	From: hoosier@commercial.com
	[other headers]
	Message-ID: <several_characters_and_numbers@site.com>

	In your new article, include the following line in your
	header:

	Supersedes: several_characters_and_numbers@site.com

	An easier way for those who use rn, trn, or nn as your
	newsreader--just type a capital 'C' while you are
	reading your original article.  Then, post your new
	article (if any).  Hitting 'C' cancels the original
	article.  Some sites have other ways of cancelling
	articles.  Talk to a local system administrator for
	help.
	


